In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class to return a custom `Window`, then override its lifecycle methods:

| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI `Window` override |
|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` / `OnActivated()` |
| `OnSleep()` | `OnDeactivated()` / `OnStopped()` |
| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` |

**Example:**

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    return new MyWindow(new AppShell());
}

// MyWindow.cs
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated()    { base.OnCreated();    /* OnStart equivalent */ }
    protected override void OnActivated()  { base.OnActivated();  }
    protected override void OnDeactivated(){ base.OnDeactivated(); /* OnSleep equivalent */ }
    protected override void OnResumed()    { base.OnResumed();     /* OnResume equivalent */ }
    protected override void OnStopped()    { base.OnStopped();    }
    protected override void OnDestroying() { base.OnDestroying(); }
}
```

For **platform-specific** hooks, you can also use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnResume(activity => { /* ... */ }));
#elif IOS
    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.WillEnterForeground(app => { /* ... */ }));
#endif
});
```
